[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Dear Chessable User,  Thank you for selecting my London System Lifetime Repertoire for White. My goal here is to provide the student with a complete system for White to play against the most common setups after 1.d4. As this is my first Chessable course, needless to say, I have put in a lot of time and effort to make this repertoire as fresh and interesting as possible. I hope you will find it useful for your games for many decades to come!  About The London System  The London System provides a solid and versatile setup for White. It is often determined by the moves d4, Nf3, Bf4, e3, and can be used against almost any opening from Black. The London System has stood the test of time at all levels. GM Kamsky has employed this opening regularly for more than a decade. The London System has been picked up and studied heavily in the past few years by several top-level Grand Masters such as Jobava, Rapport, Aronian, and also the world champion Magnus Carlsen, who scored many important and beautiful victories with it. Thanks to those efforts, the London System has become a very popular opening that deserves serious attention.  The London System is especially suited for players who want to invest the least amount of time into opening preparation and study a system-based opening that leads to a safe and playable position for White. Although the amount of theory in the London System is significantly less than that of other openings, there are still many positional nuances and tactical traps you must be aware of to employ this system successfully.  About Me  I learned chess at the age of six, and have competed professionally for more than 20 years. I achieved my highest rating of 2739 in August 2017. My best ranking is #21 in the world in October and December 2017. My most well-known tournament victory is probably the World Blitz Championship in 2013, although I have had several memorable victories in classical chess such as Asian Continental Championship 2019, World Open 2019, Saint Louis Summer Classic 2019, etc. I still remain an active top-30 player to date, however, I have recently taken a new job as the Director and Head Coach of the Chess Team at Webster University.  I made this course to share my knowledge with you, and also because I wanted to explore this opening a bit more. I knew and played the London System for White from time to time before, but I did not take it too seriously until I started working on this repertoire. During the course of my work, I was pleasantly surprised when I found many novelties and improvements that gave White comfortable positions. I now understand that if Black is not well prepared against the London System  (and I am sure many players are not, just as I wasn’t before producing this course)  , they will not be able to equalize. To prove this concept, I have tested my own recommendations against many top-level opponents such as Aronian, Mamedyarov, Svider, Firouzja, etc, and I achieved instant success. The London System brought me many nice wins especially in the Chessable Masters, as you will see from the Model Games.  Now, it is your turn to try this exciting opening. I hope you will have as much fun playing it as I have!  Liem Quang Le  Saint Louis, Missouri, USA  September 2021 }
