[Black "Structure and Sources"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ I produced this course from my own research and analyses developed mainly during this year. I used the Correspondence Database, Mega Database, and TWIC as my references; Stockfish 14 and LcZero as my engines. This course is divided into six main parts as follows:   •Part I: Kingside Fianchetto Setups, when Black starts with 1…Nf6 followed by  2.--  g6   •Part II: Nimzo/QGD Setups, when Black starts with 1…Nf6 followed by  2.--  e6  and  3.--  d5   •Part III: Queen’s Indian Setups, when Black starts with 1…Nf6 followed by  2.--  e6  and  3.--  b6   •Part IV: Slav Setups, when Black starts with 1…Nf6 followed by  2.--  d5  or vice versa   •Part V: Other setups with  1…d5  and delayed …Nf6   •Part VI: Dutch Defence Setups, when Black starts with  1…f5  followed by …e6 or …g6 at some point.   Additionally, I annotated a handful ofmodel games that I believe are highly instructive. By learning how the top-level Grand Masters handled the London System for both colors, you will develop a good understanding and feel more comfortable with these positions.  As you can see, the course structure encompasses a wide range of setups from Black. I am not saying that White has an advantage in the London System, but in general, you will likely get playable positions and avoid any opening surprises. In many cases, the arising positions after the opening are objectively equal, but slightly easier to play for White. Black can very rarely repeat the moves or exchange significant material, therefore, a fighting game is almost always guaranteed.  Let me also confess that I did not cover a few unusual first moves such as  1…b6  ,  1…d6  , or  1…g6  . These moves, while playable, are rare and uncritical to the London System. In my opinion, if Black does not fight for the e4-square, White should continue with principled chess and occupy the center immediately with  2.e4  . This approach, however, shall transpose the game to other openings such as the Pirc Defence, the Philidor Defence, or Owen’s Defence.   As those defences are totally unrelated to the London System and they may deserve a separate course, I decided not to incorporate all the subtleties and different move orders of those openings into this London System course. Having said that, I analyzed a little bit of the Pirc Defence in the 3…Bg7 variation of Part I. You can use this setup to answer the unusual first moves mentioned above. }
