[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... Bg7 4. e4
{ White should gain space in the center immediately if we are allowed to do so. }
4... d6
{ This move leads to a variation of the Pirc Defence, which Black can achieve via various move orders. I am not going to analyze this opening too deeply, as it is outside the scope of the London System. There are many options that give a small advantage for White. For the purpose of this course, I am recommending the most natural way to continue. }
5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O Nc6
{ With this move, Black prepares for ...e5 to fight for the center. } 7. d5
{ White should attack this knight and gain more space. } 7... Nb8
{ If  7...Ne5  8.Nxe5  dxe5  9.Bc4  White has a space advantage. The a1-h8 diagonal is closed, so the bishop on g7 is a bit passive. White should continue with Qe2, a4, Be3 and play on the queenside. Whenever Black plays ...f5, White should keep the center closed with f3. }
8. Be3
{ We have better development and more space on the queenside. We will continue with a4, Nf3-d2-c4, and have complete control all over the board. }
