1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good for Black, as it leads to an inferior version of the Benoni Defence. }
4. d5
{ White needs to fight for space advantage immediately. With the pawn on c2 now instead of on c4 in many Benoni variations, White has more flexible options here. As a general rule, White should meet ...a6 with a4, and play for the central break with e2-e4-e5. The f3-knight can also be relocated to c4 via d2. }
4... Bg7 5. e4 d6
{ If Black does not play this move, White should go for e5 and then h2-h4-h5 and build up a dangerous kingside attack. }
6. Bb5+
{ The purpose of this move is to disrupt Black's coordination.  6...Nbd7  7.a4  a6  8.Be2  is clearly better for White, as Black does not have counterplay with either ...b5 or ...e6. The knight on d7 also makes it harder for Black to develop his light-squared bishop. }
6... Bd7 7. a4
{ White wants to recapture on b5 with the pawn and open up the a-file. } 7...
Bxb5 8. axb5 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2
{ White has a small advantage with a clear plan to open up the center: to play for Rd1, h3, Bf4, e5. }
