1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... d5
{ This is the most principled and popular response. Black prevents e4 and argues that the knight on c3 is slightly misplaced as it stands in the way of the white c-pawn. However, the drawback of 3...d5 is that it is now harder for Black to open up the long diagonal a1-h8, thus the bishop on g7 is not very useful. Most Grunfeld or KID players would prefer playing ...c5 rather than ...d5. }
4. Bf4 { As usual, this is the best square for the London bishop. } 4... c6
{ Black usually does not play this move too early, as he wants to preserve a tempo for ...c5 }
5. h3
{ White should be accurate with the move order.  5.e3  would allow Black two extra options with  5...Bg4  or  5...Nh5  , both of which lead to satisfactory positions for Black. }
5... Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White can develop normally, castle and then expand on the queenside with a4-a5.  7...Qb6  should be met with  8.Rb1  . This is the best way to defend the b2-pawn. Later on, White can play b2-b4-b5 to open up the queenside.  8...Nbd7  9.O-O  . The black queen is slightly misplaced on b6. }
7... Nbd7 { This is the most flexible move for Black. } 8. O-O Re8 9. Bh2
{ I like this prophylactic move. We retreat our London bishop to a safer place while maintaining flexibility with all other queenside plans. }
9... a5 10. a4 b6 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bd3
{ With natural moves White has a small advantage. Now we want to play e4, while it is not so easy to come up with a plan for Black. }
12... c5
{ This move is premature as it gives away the very important b5-square. } 13.
Nb5 Rc8 14. b3
{ All White's pieces are very well placed. We want to continue with Rc1 and c4 to fight for the center. Black has a hard time coming up with any useful move. }
