1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... d5
{ This is the most principled and popular response. Black prevents e4 and argues that the knight on c3 is slightly misplaced as it stands in the way of the white c-pawn. However, the drawback of 3...d5 is that it is now harder for Black to open up the long diagonal a1-h8, thus the bishop on g7 is not very useful. Most Grunfeld or KID players would prefer playing ...c5 rather than ...d5. }
4. Bf4 { As usual, this is the best square for the London bishop. } 4... Bg7
{ This is Black's best continuation. Other than 4...Bg7 and  4...c6  , all other moves are questionable. }
5. Nb5
{ White takes advantage of the fact that Black has not castled yet to attack c7, when Black does not have Ne8. }
5... Na6
{ This move is forced to defend c7. As this knight on a6 is slightly misplaced, Black will have to spend time later to regroup it. }
6. e3
{ White continues with normal development. Our knight can go back to c3 when needed. }
6... O-O 7. h3
{ The benefit of this move is twofold: preventing Bg4 and Nh5, as it creates the h2-square for the bishop on f4 to retreat if needed. }
7... c6 8. Nc3
{ This is the critical position for this chapter. Black now has several plans to choose from. }
8... Nc7
{ This is a natural knight retreat. However, I am not sure where the knight is heading to. }
9. Bd3
{ White continues normal development. The bishop is useful on d3 as it can support e4 later. }
9... Nce8
{ Black takes time to relocate this knight to d6, where it has good control over the center. The drawback is that it will be almost impossible for Black to play ...e5. }
10. O-O Nd6 11. a4
{ Typical move to gain space on the queenside. If Black does not stop this pawn, White plans for a5, Qd2, Na4, etc. }
11... a5
{ This move stops a5, but it weakens the b5-square in case Black wants to play ...c5 in the future. }
12. Ne2
{ It is time to prepare for queenside expansion with either b3, c4 or c3, b4. If  12...Bf5  13.b3  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  . White will play c4 next move and enjoy more space in the center. }
12... b6 13. c3 c5
{ This move is logical, but it does not stop White's next move. } 14. b4
{ This is a very rich and original position with all pieces on the board. White wants to open up the queenside. }
14... axb4 15. cxb4 c4
{ As Black is behind in development, he should keep the queenside closed. } 16.
Bc2 Bb7 17. b5
{ White has good chances to create a passed pawn on the queenside with Qd1-b1-b4, Nc3, doubling rooks on the a-file or playing for e4, etc. With a relatively closed position, the c4-pawn does not do much. While I believe White has easier play, it remains an open battle where any result is possible. }
