1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... c5
{ This move often transposes to one of the lines in this chapter or the next chapter. Here we will investigate Black's options which lead to an independent variation. }
4. c3
{ This is the most accurate move order. White is ready to recapture on d4 with our c-pawn and keep a symmetrical pawn structure.  4...d5  5.e3  is discussed in this chapter, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/3P1B2/2P2N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b6  5.e3  Bb7  6.Bd3  is the topic of thenext chapter. }
4... Qb6
{ This queen move should be countered by an offer to exchange queens and improve White's pawn structure. }
5. Qb3
{ Black must now make a decision whether to allow White to capture on b6.   5...d5  6.e3  transposes toanother line.   5...Qxb3  is not good as White has a superior pawn structure after  6.axb3  cxd4  7.Nxd4  .   If  5...Nc6  6.e3  d5  7.Nbd2  Be7  8.h3  O-O  then  9.Be2  transposes to the5...Qb6 move order. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxb6
{ Black's queenside is compromised with this queen exchange. } 6... axb6 7.
Nxd4
{ Black must be careful here as White has some threats connected with Nb5. }
7... d5 8. Nb5 Na6 { This move is forced to defend against Nc7+ } 9. f3
{ This move takes control of the e4-square, so Black does not have Ne4 or Bc5 hitting the f2-pawn once White castles long. }
9... Bd7 10. N1a3 { The white knights protect each other very well. } 10... Bc5
11. O-O-O O-O 12. Kb1 Bc6 13. g4
{ This position is complex but easier to play for White. First of all, White has a clear plan to develop our pieces and start an attack on the kingside. In the meantime, the black knight on a6 does not have a bright future. }
