1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... d5 4. c3
{ You can also start with 4. e3 and then 5. c3. In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... Bd6 { It is useful for Black to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 5. e3
{ White should not be afraid of the double f-pawns. } 5... Bxf4 6. exf4
{ White has nice control in the center and excellent attacking prospects on the kingside. The pawn on f4 helps White control the very important e5-square. }
6... O-O 7. Nbd2 c5
{ This move challenges White's center. Usually White should accept this exchange unless Black can recapture on c5 with his b-pawn. }
8. dxc5 Qc7 9. g3
{ It is more important to keep the f4-pawn than the c5-pawn as the f4-pawn is more useful in controlling the center.  9...Qxc5  10.Bd3  is slightly better for White. White will continue with O-O, Re1, Nd2-b3-d4, Ne5, with active play. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nb3
{ White should be happy to exchange a pair of knights.  10...Nxc5  11.Nxc5  Qxc5  12.Bd3  , White is slightly better as our pieces are more active. }
10... a5 11. Bg2
{ This is a rare case where White wants the bishop on g2 instead of d3, so the knight on c5 does not hit the bishop. }
11... a4 12. Nbd4 Nxc5 13. O-O
{ White's pieces are slightly better placed. We will continue with Re1, Qc2, Rad1. Black will always have to watch out for the f5 break. }
*

