1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... d5 4. c3
{ You can also start with 4. e3 and then 5. c3. In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is the main tabiya of this chapter. Black has several playable options here. However, there are many subtleties in all of those variations that Black must know well to fully equalize. }
6... Bd6
{ This move remains the most common one for Black, although its popularity has gone down a bit recently. }
7. Bg3
{ As usual, White wants to invite Black to capture on g3 and open the h-file for our rook. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6
{ This is the old main line. Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 to control e4. }
9. e4
{ I believe this move puts Black's setup to a real test. White takes advantage of the slightly weaken a8-h1 diagonal and immediately opens up the center. }
9... Be7 { Black retreats his bishop and tries to keep the kingside closed. }
10. e5
{ White gains space and forces the black knight away from the defensive square on f6. }
10... Nh5
{ Black does not necessarily want to exchange the London bishop, but he rather wants to keep the knight closer to his king. If given time, Black is going to follow up with ...g6 and ...f5 to close the b1-h7 diagonal. }
11. Ng5
{ Without this move, White does not have any advantage. Black must capture the white knight now as White is attacking both the h7-pawn and the knight on h5. }
11... Bxg5
{ 11...Nxg3  12.Bxh7+  Kh8  13.Nxf7+!  Rxf7  14.hxg3  wins for White. } 12.
Qxh5 g6
{ This move is forced to defend the h7-pawn.  12...h6  13.Nf3  leaves Black in a very difficult position. White will play h4, Bf4, Rh1-Rh3-Rg3 with a deadly attack on the black king. }
13. Qe2
{ Now that the black g-pawn has moved up, White is ready for h2-h4-h5 to open up the h-file. }
13... cxd4 14. h4
{ White sacrifices a pawn but has a great attack. The black bishop has three squares to go now, but none of them can give him full equality. }
14... Bh6 { This move is just asking for the white pawn to advance further }
15. h5 dxc3 16. bxc3 Bg7
{ The black bishop is a good defending piece here, but it is passive.  16...g5  17.Nf3  with the idea of Nh2-Ng4 looks dangerous for Black. }
17. Nf3
{ White should go Kf1, Re1 to protect our central pawn, then continue the kingside attack with Qd2, Bg3-Bf4-Bh6. The position is very hard to defend for Black. }
