[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ This is the preferred move order for players who like to play Queen's Indian for Black. Peter Leko is one of the top GMs who employs this system consistently. With this setup, Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 or sometimes trade the light-squared bishops with Ba6. He usually follows up with ...c5 and ...cxd4. Black's d-pawn often goes to d6, and Black aims for a solid position with potential ...e5 break later on. }
4. e3 Nh5
{ This move is premature because Black cannot exchange his knight with the London bishop. }
5. Bg5 Be7 6. Ne5
{ White is attacking the black knight as well as creating a threat of Qf3. }
6... Nf6 { The black knight must retreat to cover the f7-square. } 7. Qf3
{ White should play aggressively and start an attack immediately. } 7... c6 8.
h4
{ White has good prospect on the kingside. We will play Nc3, O-O-O, Bd3, potentially h4-h5-h6. The black king will not be safe. }
