[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ This is the preferred move order for players who like to play Queen's Indian for Black. Peter Leko is one of the top GMs who employs this system consistently. With this setup, Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 or sometimes trade the light-squared bishops with Ba6. He usually follows up with ...c5 and ...cxd4. Black's d-pawn often goes to d6, and Black aims for a solid position with potential ...e5 break later on. }
4. e3 Bb7
{ This move is a logical follow-up of the previous move. However, I also analyzed a few other options for Black. }
5. Bd3
{ I am recommending this move for White. We delay the move Nbd2 because this knight may be better placed on c3 in some cases, as you will see later. We should prioritize developing our kingside and aiming for e3-e4. }
5... Be7
{ Black develops his bishop naturally and creates the positional threat of ...Nh5 at the same time. }
6. h3
{ This standard move neutralizes the Nh5 threat by allowing our bishop a retreat to h2 when necessary. }
6... c5 7. c3
{ White is ready to recapture on d4 with the c-pawn, thus giving the c3-square for our knight. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Similarly to 7...cxd4, if  8...cxd4  White should recapture with the c-pawn.  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  d5  11.Nc3  transposes tothis line in Part III. }
8... d5
{ This move is not the most popular, but in my opinion the soundest continuation for Black. It may look a bit unnatural to close the long diagonal, but Black needs to prevent White from playing e4. The black knight can develop to c6 or d7, and Black can also try to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bd6. }
9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. a4
{ This is a typical move to gain space on the queenside. 11. a5 is a positional threat. }
10... a6
{ This move prevents White's idea. If  11.a5?!  b5  , Black has a solid position with no weakness. }
11. Qb1
{ This move controls the e4-square and supports b4. White is ready to start the queenside battle. The natural-looking  11...h6  is strongly met by  12.b4  cxb4  13.cxb4  , and White has a clear plan on the queenside: Qb2, Rfc1, b5, Nf3-Ne5-Nc6, etc. }
11... c4
{ Black attempts to expand on the queenside with this move. Now White has to retreat the bishop and allow Black's next move. }
12. Bc2 b5 13. b4
{ Black is faced with a tough decision here: closing the queenside would lead to a passive position, but opening the queenside would leave him with a weakness on b5. }
13... cxb3
{ This move simplifies the position but Black may have a hard time defending his b5-pawn. }
14. Qxb3 Bc6
{ The black bishop must go here to defend the b5-pawn and creates the threat of ...bxa4. }
15. axb5 axb5
{ This move keeps a good control over the c4-square. However, the pawn is vulnerable on b5 and the black bishop is relatively passive on c6. }
16. Bd3 { White should target this pawn immediately. } 16... Qb6 17. Rfb1
{ We have reached a playable middlegame. The position is objectively equal, but the b5-pawn is a clear target for White. It is harder for Black to attack the c3-pawn. }
