1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ 2...Nf6  3.c3  transposes toPart IV: Slav Setup. In this chapter, we will study Black's moves other than 2...Nf6. As a general rule, if Black makes unambitious moves, at some point White should play actively with  c4  and gain space on the queenside. }
2... Bf5
{ This bishop development is premature, as White's next move immediately highlights Black's queenside weakness. }
3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qb3
{ White attacks the b7-pawn, which is left undefended because the black bishop is no longer on c8. Black must defend this pawn with his queen now. }
5... Qb6 { This move invites White to gain more space with } 6. c5 Qxb3 7. axb3
Nd7 8. b4 { White threatens b5 and weakens the black pawn on c6. } 8... a6 9.
Bf4 Rc8 10. Nd2
