[Black "Dutch Defence #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence is one of the most common responses to White's first move. The London System still works as a charm here, but we must be accurate with our move order. }
2. Nf3
{ It is preferable to develop this knight before the London bishop, so we have more flexibility in case Black does something unusual. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ It is best to develop the London bishop first. White should only play c4, Nc3 after Black plays g6 or after White castles. }
3... e6
{ With this move, Black announces his intention not to fianchetto the kingside bishop. }
4. e3
{ White should not rush with c4 as that would allow Black the possibility to develop his bishop to b4 without being kicked away. }
4... Be7 5. h3 { This is a prophylactic move against Nh5. } 5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ The bishop is best placed here to support a potential e4 break. } 6... b6 7.
O-O Bb7 8. c4
{ After castling, White should play this move to gain space on the queenside and prepare to put our knight on c3. }
8... Ne4 9. Nfd2 { White should exchange this active knight immediately. } 9...
Nxd2 10. Qxd2
{ Our other knight needs to go to c3 to control the central squares of e4 and d5. }
10... d6 11. Nc3 Nd7 12. Bh2 { White is ready for the e4 break. } 12... e5
{ If Black does not play this move, he would have a very difficult position once White gets e4 in. }
13. Qc2 e4 14. Be2 Kh8 15. b4
{ The long diagonal is closed, so White now starts a queenside attack with Rab1 and c5 next. Black does not have a clear plan at all. If Black tries to open the kingside with ...f4, the e4-pawn would likely fall. }
