[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Part I: Kingside Fianchetto"]
[Black "3...Bg7 4.e4 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... Bg7 4. e4
{ White should gain space in the center immediately if we are allowed to do so. }
4... d5
{ This move challenges the white pawn on e4, but allows us to gain more space. }
5. e5 Ne4 6. Bd3
{ We allow Black to double our c-pawns, but retain a strong center. Moreover, the black bishop does nothing on g7 as White has a strong pawn chain with c3-d4-e5. White can attack on both flanks later, with potential h2-h4-h5 on the kingside, or a4 followed by Ba3, Rb1 on the queenside. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. O-O Qa5
{ Developing the queen this early is usually not a good idea. } 9. a4
{ We do not need to defend the c3-pawn, and should continue our plan to attack on the queenside.  9...Qxc3  is a mistake as the black queen is trapped after  10.Bd2  Qb2  11.Rb1  Qa2  12.Qc1  followed by Ra1.  12...Qxa4  does not help because of  13.Bb5+  . }
9... O-O 10. Ba3
{ From here, the white bishop attacks the black pawn on c5 and potentially the e7-pawn as well. }
10... c4
{ This move closes the queenside and keeps the pawn for Black, but now White has a free hand on the kingside. }
11. Be2 Nc6 12. Qd2
{ White can play Rfb1 or Nh4 followed by f4-f5 with a strong attack on the kingside. Black does not have any clear counterplay. }
