[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we will learn what to do against Black's kingside fianchetto setup. This is the preferred move order for someone who is ready to play King's Indian Defence or Grunfeld Defence. Generally speaking, Black wants to castle short and generate counterplay in the center with either ...c5 or ...e5. }
3. Nc3
{ I am recommending this dynamic move. White threatens to play 4.e4 and dominate the center. This concrete approach has been employed numerous times recently by many top GMs, most notably Aronian. He scored important victories against strong opposition such as Vachier, Nepomniachtchi, Rapport, Jones, etc. }
3... d5
{ This is the most principled and popular response. Black prevents e4 and argues that the knight on c3 is slightly misplaced as it stands in the way of the white c-pawn. However, the drawback of 3...d5 is that it is now harder for Black to open up the long diagonal a1-h8, thus the bishop on g7 is not very useful. Most Grunfeld or KID players would prefer playing ...c5 rather than ...d5. }
4. Bf4 { As usual, this is the best square for the London bishop. } 4... Bg7
{ This is Black's best continuation. Other than 4...Bg7 and  4...c6  , all other moves are questionable. }
5. Nb5
{ White attacks c7 and takes advantage of the fact that Black has not castled yet as Ne8 is not possible. }
5... Na6
{ This move is forced to defend c7. As this knight on a6 is slightly misplaced, Black will have to spend time later to regroup it. }
6. e3
{ White continues with normal development. Our knight can go back to c3 when needed. }
6... O-O 7. h3
{ The benefit of this move is twofold: preventing Bg4 and Nh5, as it creates the h2-square for the bishop on f4 to retreat if needed. }
7... Ne4
{ This logical move has become popular lately. Black controls the c3-square and threatens ...c6. White has two good ways to respond:  8.c3  or  8.Nd2  . It was a difficult decision to make, but in the end, I chose the latter as I felt that the arising position is easier to understand. Interested White players may want to investigate 8.c3 further if they are not happy with 8.Nd2 for some reason. }
8. Nd2 { White should exchange the Black's active knight. } 8... c6
{ Black is willing to double his own pawns in exchange for counterplay against White's center and along the long diagonal a1-h8. }
9. Nxe4
{ White must exchange this knight, so our other knight can retreat safely to c3 without doubling our c-pawns. }
9... dxe4
{ 9...cxb5  leads to a difficult position for Black after the simple response  10.Nd2  b4  11.a3  . White has the better pawn structure and more active pieces. }
10. Nc3 c5 { This is the only way to justify Black's 8th move. } 11. Nxe4
{ This is a natural novelty. White captures the pawn immediately and asks Black to show his compensation. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4 Bxd4
{ This move allows White to complete development in a harmonious way. } 13. c3
Nc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Bc4
{ The bishop is perfectly placed here to target Black's kingside. } 15... Qb6
16. Qe2
{ White has more active pieces. The plan is to castle short and bring our rooks to d1 and e1. We can also potentially create a passed pawn on the queenside later on. }
