5... Na6
{ This move is forced to defend c7. As this knight on a6 is slightly misplaced, Black will have to spend time later to regroup it. }
6. e3
{ White continues with normal development. Our knight can go back to c3 when needed. }
6... O-O 7. h3
{ The benefit of this move is twofold: preventing Bg4 and Nh5, as it creates the h2-square for the bishop on f4 to retreat if needed. }
7... Ne4
{ This logical move has become popular lately. Black controls the c3-square and threatens ...c6. White has two good ways to respond:  8.c3  or  8.Nd2  . It was a difficult decision to make, but in the end, I chose the latter as I felt that the arising position is easier to understand. Interested White players may want to investigate 8.c3 further if they are not happy with 8.Nd2 for some reason. }
8. Nd2 { White should exchange the Black's active knight. } 8... c6
{ Black is willing to double his own pawns in exchange for counterplay against White's center and along the long diagonal a1-h8. }
9. Nxe4
{ White must exchange this knight, so our other knight can retreat safely to c3 without doubling our c-pawns. }
9... dxe4
{ 9...cxb5  leads to a difficult position for Black after the simple response  10.Nd2  b4  11.a3  . White has the better pawn structure and more active pieces. }
10. Nc3 c5 { This is the only way to justify Black's 8th move. } 11. Nxe4
{ This is a natural novelty. White captures the pawn immediately and asks Black to show his compensation. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4 Qd5
{ This move, as well as the next one, are very important. Black must drive away the white knight from the center before recapturing on d4. Otherwise, White would have very active pieces. }
13. Nc3 Qxd4 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nd5
{ White's knight is very annoying on d5. If White has time to castle long, Black is positionally lost. Therefore, Black must sacrifice the e7-pawn. }
15... Rd8 16. Nxe7+ Kf8 17. Nxc8 Bxb2
{ Otherwise, White will castle long and has a clear advantage thanks to the bishop pair and queenside pawn majority. }
18. Bh6+ { This move forces Black to exchange the bishops. } 18... Bg7 19.
Bxg7+ Kxg7 20. Bxa6 bxa6
{ Black will recapture the white knight, but we will use that time to finish our development. }
21. Ne7
{ 21.Nxa7  wins a pawn only temporarily, as after  21...Rxa7  22.O-O  Rc7  23.Rfc1  Rdc8  Black wins it back. Instead of that pawn, White should try to connect the rooks and keep the passed c-pawn, which is our most important asset in this endgame. }
21... Re8 22. O-O-O Rxe7 23. Rhe1
{ As Black has double a-pawns, we can consider that White is up a pawn. With best play, Black should be able to hold this endgame. However, it is still not easy to defend. Our plan is to activate the rooks, exchange one pair of rooks and start advancing the c-pawn. For instance, after  23...Rb7  24.Re3  , White wants to follow up with Rd6 or Rb3. If White can exchange a pair of rooks, White has excellent winning chances with the dangerous passed pawn. }
