{ This move allows White to gain more space in the center immediately. } 3. d5
{ This position is outside the scope of London System, so I am not going to analyze it too deeply. For the purpose of our course, I will briefly outline the plans for White, just in case you face this unlikely and questionable move order from Black.   First of all, if Black does not play 3...b5, then White should play Nc3 followed by e4, with total domination in the center. White should always meet ...a6 with a4, and then try to bring the other knight to c4 @@StartBracket@@Nf3-d2-c4@@EndBracket@@.   Secondly, if Black plays  3...b5  here, White can sacrifice a pawn with  4.e4  , and has tremendous compensation. }
3... b5
{ This move gains space for Black on the queenside. Now White should play aggressively with }
4. e4
{ This move is relatively rare but very strong. White sacrifices a pawn for quick development. }
4... Nxe4 5. Bd3
{ White does not need to take the b5-pawn yet. It is more important to develop with tempo. Black's knight has to move again for the third time in the opening. }
5... Qa5+
{ This move saves the pawn for Black and allows his knight to drop back to f6. }
6. Nbd2 { White should continue developing our pieces } 6... Nf6
{ Black must retreat his knight and try to keep up with the development. } 7.
O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn for the attack. Black must be very careful here to avoid a quick defeat. We have almost completed our development, while Black has managed to get out only his queen and knight. }
7... Bb7 { White should meet this move with an aggressive response. } 8. c4
{ This move defends the d5-pawn and also attacks Black's b5-pawn. } 8... e6 9.
Ne4
{ As a general rule, when attacking we should centralize all our pieces and exchange our opponent's most active pieces. }
9... bxc4 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bxc4
{ White has a great attack in exchange for only a pawn. White will play Re1, Bf4 next and go after the black king. }
*

