[Black "2...c5 3.d5 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5
{ This move allows White to gain more space in the center immediately. In my opinion, this approach is slightly questionable for Black. }
3. d5 e6
{ This move leads to the Benoni Defence. The position is outside the scope of London System, so I am not going to analyze it too deeply. For the purpose of our course, I will recommend a simple way to secure a small advantage for White. }
4. Nc3
{ I like this move the most, although there is nothing wrong with 4. c4, transposing to regular Benoni. The idea of 4. Nc3 is to fight for control in the center right away and to save the c4-square for the knight or the bishop. }
4... d6
{ This move allows White to play e4 and increase the control over the center. }
5. e4 exd5 6. exd5
{ White should recapture with this pawn to seize more space in the center. }
6... Be7 7. Be2
{ In the long term, the white knight can come to c4 and attack the black pawn on d6. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Na6
{ This is a normal move in Benoni pawn structure, but here White can respond with }
9. Bxa6 bxa6 10. Qd3
{ White has a clear advantage thanks to Black's weaknesses on a6 and d6. White plans to play h3, Re1, Bf4 next. Black does not have any counterplay. }
*

