1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5
{ This move allows White to gain more space in the center immediately. In my opinion, this approach is slightly questionable for Black. }
3. d5 e6
{ This move leads to the Benoni Defence. The position is outside the scope of London System, so I am not going to analyze it too deeply. For the purpose of our course, I will recommend a simple way to secure a small advantage for White. }
4. Nc3
{ I like this move the most, although there is nothing wrong with 4. c4, transposing to regular Benoni. The idea of 4. Nc3 is to fight for control in the center right away and to save the c4-square for the knight or the bishop. }
4... exd5
{ This move releases the tension in the center but allows the white queen to centralize. }
5. Nxd5 Nxd5 6. Qxd5
{ The white queen is very active on d5 and cannot be chased away easily. } 6...
Be7 { This move is too slow. } 7. Bf4
{ White establishes control of the d6-square with this move. If Black cannot play ... d6, he will not be able to complete his development. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O
{ If 8... O-O then 9. Bd6 Bxd6 10. Qxd6, the black pawn on c5 becomes weak. White will soon follow up with e4, Bc4 and control everything. }
8... Nb4 9. Qb3 d6
{ Black wants to attack the white queen with ... Be6, but there is a simple solution. }
10. e4
{ ... Be6 can be met by Bc4. The game may continue with 10... O-O 11. a3 Nc6 12. e5 d5 13. Qxd5, when White wins a pawn and retains a clear advantage. }
