[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... c5
{ This move often transposes to one of the lines in this chapter or the next chapter. Here we will investigate Black's options which lead to an independent variation. }
4. c3
{ This is the most accurate move order. White is ready to recapture on d4 with our c-pawn and keep a symmetrical pawn structure.  4...d5  5.e3  is discussed in this chapter, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/3P1B2/2P2N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b6  5.e3  Bb7  6.Bd3  is the topic of thenext chapter. }
4... cxd4 5. cxd4
{ This position is very similar to the Slav Exchange. The black light-squared bishop is passive on c8, which gives White good chances to fight for a small advantage. }
5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d5 7. e3 Bd6 8. Bg3
{ This is the typical way to meet Bd6. Black does not want to capture on g3 before White castles because that would open up the h-file for the white rook. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. Rc1
{ White should delay castling to discourage Black from taking on g3. } 10...
Bb7 11. Bh4
{ White creates an unpleasant pin and forces the black bishop to retreat with }
11... Be7 12. O-O Rc8 13. a3
{ White's plan is relatively simple: to play on the queenside with our better pieces. }
*

