5... cxd4 6. Qxb6
{ Black's queenside is compromised with this queen exchange. } 6... axb6 7.
Nxd4
{ Black must be careful here as White has some threats connected with Nb5. }
7... Be7 8. Nb5 Na6 { This move is forced to defend against Nc7. } 9. Nd6+ Bxd6
10. Bxd6 { White gets the bishop pair and the better pawn structure. } 10...
Ne4 11. Ba3 d5 12. f3 Nec5 13. Nd2 O-O 14. e4
{ White should open up the center for our bishops. White has slightly better chances in this position as it is not easy for Black to come up with a plan to regroup his pieces. White will castle long and play against Black's d5-pawn. }
