{ I have made this move the main line to remind you that we can also achieve this position via a transposition inPart IV. However, you can also start with  4.e3  and then 5.c3  . In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Qb6
{ This move attacks the b2-pawn. As the white knight is not on d2 yet, we do not have Rb1. Therefore, we must defend the pawn with our queen. }
6. Qb3
{ This move is better than  6.Qc2  because it stops Black from exchanging the bishops with ...Bd6. }
6... Be7
{ Black develops normally and creates the positional threat of ...Nh5. } 7. h3
{ It is important to preserve our London bishop. Now  7...Nh5  does not make sense because of  8.Bh2  . }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Be2
{ This bishop should stay on e2 instead of d3 so White does not have to exchange queens in case of ...c4. If Black exchanges our pawn with  9...cxd4  10.exd4  , White will solidify our center and open up the e-file for our rook. }
