6. Nbd2 { If  6...Nc6  7.Bg3  transposes to the main line below. } 6... O-O 7.
Bg3
{ After Black castles, White should keep this bishop on g3. Exchanging the bishops then would open the h-file for the white rook to attack Black's kingside. }
7... Qc7
{ This is a clever move order. Black prepares for Nbd7, with the e5 idea, without forcing the exchanges of the bishops or central pawns. }
8. dxc5
{ White should take this pawn now to force the black queen to waste some time. }
8... Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Qe2
{ White prepares for e4 and long castle with this move. } 10... Bxg3
{ It is better for Black to exchange the bishops before playing ...e5, however, the drawback of this move is that the white rook becomes stronger. }
11. hxg3 e5
{ This is the critical move, however Black must know it really well to avoid trouble. }
12. e4 Qb6
{ With this move, Black gains a tempo by attacking b2 and preparing for ... Nc5. }
13. O-O-O Re8
{ Black defends his d5-pawn indirectly.  14.exd5  is a mistake because of  14...e4  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  f5  , winning material for  Black. }
14. Rh4 { By defending the e4-square, White renews the threat of exd5. } 14...
Nc5 15. exd5 e4
{ Both sides must play a series of forcing moves to avoid losing on the spot. }
16. Nxe4 Nfxe4 17. Bxe4 f5
{ Black wins the bishop, but White has just enough resources to force a draw. }
18. d6
{ No matter how Black captures the bishop now, White can get a repetition through tactics. }
18... Rxe4
{ 18...fxe4  19.Ng5  White threatens Qh5, so Black's response is forced.  19...h6  20.Rxh6  gxh6  21.Qh5  hxg5  22.Qxe8+  White has sacrificed a lot of material to expose Black's king.  22...Kg7  23.Qe7+  Kg6  24.Qe8+  Black is two pieces up, but he cannot avoid perpetual checks. }
19. Rxe4 fxe4 20. Ng5
{ White threatens both Qc4+ and Qh5, so Black's response is forced. } 20... h6
21. Qc4+ Kh8 22. Nf7+ Kh7 23. b4
{ If the knight moves to any square other than d3, White would simply capture on e4 with check.  23...Be6  does not work because of  24.bxc5  Bxc4  25.cxb6  Bxf7  26.d7  Rd8  27.bxa7  , White wins the exchange and the game with 28. a8Q and 29.d8Q. }
23... Nd3+ 24. Rxd3 exd3 25. Qxd3+ Kg8 26. Nxh6+
{ Again, White sacrificed a lot of material to expose the black king. } 26...
gxh6 27. Qg6+
{ Even though Black is up a rook and a bishop, there is no way for Black to avoid perpetual checks. From a theoretical point of view, this should be satisfying for Black. However, I feel that finding all these moves for Black starting with 11...e5 are very difficult practically. If Black makes just one mistake in this line, he would be much worse. White's moves are a lot more straightforward. }
