[White "Part II: Nimzo/QGD Setup"]
[Black "2...e6 3.Bf4 d5 4.c3 c5 5.e3 Bd6 6.Ndb2 cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... d5 4. c3
{ I have made this move the main line to remind you that we can also achieve this position via a transposition inPart IV. However, you can also start with  4.e3  and then 5.c3  . In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Bd6
{ Black offers the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. White should not waste time to move the London bishop yet.   If  6.Bg3  Qc7  7.Nbd2  Nbd7  , Black fully equalizes with ...e5 idea. }
6. Nbd2 { If  6...Nc6  7.Bg3  transposes to the main line below. } 6... cxd4
{ This move forces White to sacrifice a pawn. } 7. Bxd6
{ This pawn sacrifice has appeared only once so far. If  7...Qxd6  8.exd4  O-O  9.Bd3  . This is the type of position we are aiming for. White’s bishop is very good on d3, and we have full control of the e5-square. }
7... dxc3 { This is my attempt to improve over the gameCarlsen - Ding, 2020. }
8. Qa4+ { White tries to activate the queen and keep the bishop on d6. } 8...
Nc6 9. Qa3 cxd2+ 10. Nxd2 Bd7 11. Bd3 Qa5 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. Rc1 Qxb3 14. Nxb3
{ Even without the queens, the bishop on d6 is still quite annoying for Black. }
