1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... d5 4. c3
{ I have made this move the main line to remind you that we can also achieve this position via a transposition inPart IV. However, you can also start with  4.e3  and then 5.c3  . In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2
