[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
{ After having covered the rare idea of  2...c5  , we will now devote the rest of the chapter to studying the setup when Black is ready to play a Nimzo Indian, Ragozin Defence, or Queen's Gambit Declined. This setup is often chosen by top GMs such as Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, etc. }
3. Bf4 { As usual, White wants to develop the bishop here before playing e3. }
3... d5 4. c3
{ I have made this move the main line to remind you that we can also achieve this position via a transposition inPart IV. However, you can also start with  4.e3  and then 5.c3  . In this setup, White's main hope for advantage hinges on the fact that our bishops are slightly more active than black ones. The black bishop on c8 will normally develop to b7, where it is still not as useful as the white bishop on d3. }
4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is the main tabiya of this chapter. Black has several playable options here. However, there are many subtleties in all of those variations that Black must know well to fully equalize. }
6... Bd6
{ This move remains the most common one for Black, although its popularity has gone down a bit recently. }
7. Bg3
{ As usual, White wants to invite Black to capture on g3 and open the h-file for our rook. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 Qe7
{ With this move, Black wants to play e5. White must stop that immediately with our next move. }
9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7
{ This is a well-known mistake for Black. The refutation was shown in more than 80 games already, with the highest rated game being Kamsky - Shankland, 2014. }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+
{ This piece sacrifice is the reason why White had to lure the black queen to c5. }
13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4
{ White gains a tempo by attacking the black queen. If the black queen moves then Ng5, the black king will be in trouble. }
15... Qb5 16. Ng5 Qd3
{ This move does not help Black as White can close the d3-h7 diagonal. } 17. e4
Rfd8 18. Qxf7+ Kh8 19. Rd1 Qc2 20. O-O
{ White is totally winning as Black has no defence on the kingside. White can bring a rook to the third rank with Rde1-Re3-Rh3 and the game will be over soon. }
