{ As usual, White wants to invite Black to capture on g3 and open the h-file for our rook. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ The white bishop is best placed on d3 to support e4. Black has many options here. }
8... Re8
{ This is another way for Black to prepare for ... e5. It has been played by strong GMs such as Vitiugov and Li Chao. However, I do not think it equalizes for Black. }
9. Ne5 { This is a standard move to stop ... e5. } 9... Qc7 10. f4
{ White must fortify the e5 knight to fight for advantage. } 10... Ne7
{ This is a typical maneuver in this pawn structure. Black wants to play Nf5, Be7, Nd6 to control the e4-square. }
11. Bh4
{ White responds aggressively. The threat is Bxf6 to expose the black king. }
11... Nf5
{ This move is untimely here, but there was no logical follow up for Black. }
12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qh5
{ White has a winning attack. For instance, 13... fxe5 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 16. e4 dxe4 17. Bb5 followed by g4 wins a piece for White. }
