4... c5 5. e3 { Here Black has three main choices. } 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2
{ This is the main tabiya of this chapter. Black has several playable options here. However, there are many subtleties in all of those variations that Black must know well to fully equalize. }
6... Bd6
{ This move remains the most common one for Black, although its popularity has gone down a bit recently. }
7. Bg3
{ As usual, White wants to invite Black to capture on g3 and open the h-file for our rook. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6
{ This is the old main line. Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 to control e4. }
9. e4
{ I believe this move puts Black's setup to a real test. White takes advantage of the slightly weaken a8-h1 diagonal and immediately opens up the center. }
9... Be7 { Black retreats his bishop and tries to keep the kingside closed. }
10. e5
{ White gains space and forces the black knight away from the defensive square on f6. }
10... Nd7
{ This is not an ideal place for the knight. White can start a great attack with }
11. h4 { The immediate threat is  12.Bxh7+  followed by  13.Ng5+  . } 11... h6
{ This move parries the threat of Bxh7 but further weakens Black's kingside. }
12. O-O
{ As there is no more Ng5, White should castle and bring the rook to e1 to prepare for a potential opening of the center. }
12... a5 13. Re1 Ba6 14. Bb1
{ White should keep the light-squared bishop for the kingside attack. White is threatening Qc2 now, so Black must vacate the f8-square for his knight to defend h7. }
14... Re8 15. h5
{ The black king is very vulnerable. White plans to continue with Bf4, Nd2-Nf1-Nh2-Ng4, and potentially transferring the rook to g3 or queen to g4. }
