[White "Part III: Queen's Indian Setup"]
[Black "4...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ This is the preferred move order for players who like to play Queen's Indian for Black. Peter Leko is one of the top GMs who employs this system consistently. With this setup, Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 or sometimes trade the light-squared bishops with Ba6. He usually follows up with ...c5 and ...cxd4. Black's d-pawn often goes to d6, and Black aims for a solid position with potential ...e5 break later on. }
4. e3 c5
{ This move leads to a position which has appeared via various move orders in more than 1000 games, however, I believe it is very bad for Black. The next move by White only appeared in about 100 games, which means that many people are not aware of this refutation! }
5. Nc3
{ With this move, White immediately creates concrete threats of d5 and Nb5. Black cannot prevent both. }
5... a6 { This move prevents Nb5 but does nothing to stop White's next move. }
6. d5 Bb7
{ 6...d6  7.dxe6  fxe6  8.e4  . White has a nice advantage thanks to Black's weak pawns on d6 and b6. The immediate threat for White is 9.e5, destroying Black's pawn structure. }
7. e4 { White continues gaining space in the center. } 7... b5 8. Qe2
{ The white queen moves up to clear the first rank for our king to castle long if needed. Qe2 is better than Qd2 because it prevents ...exd5. Our light-squared bishop can later develop to g2 or h3. }
8... Qa5
{ Black creates a pin on the white knight and discourages  9.O-O-O  as Black has  9...b4  . Here I found a strong response for White. }
9. Nd2
{ This novelty solves the issue with the pin and prepares to chase away the black queen with Nb3 in the future. }
9... Be7 { Black must try to complete his development as soon as possible. }
10. g3 { Now, White should castle short and bring the rooks to the center. }
10... exd5 11. e5
{ White does not need to recapture the pawn immediately. Instead, we attack the black knight and play for the initiative. If  11...Nh5  12.Bg2  Nxf4  13.gxf4  followed by 14. Nd5, White totally dominates in the center. }
11... Ne4 12. Ndxe4 dxe4 13. Bg2
{ White has a clear advantage We will play O-O next move followed by Nxe4, Qg4 with a dangerous kingside attack. }
