[White "Part III: Queen's Indian Setup"]
[Black "4...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ This is the preferred move order for players who like to play Queen's Indian for Black. Peter Leko is one of the top GMs who employs this system consistently. With this setup, Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 or sometimes trade the light-squared bishops with Ba6. He usually follows up with ...c5 and ...cxd4. Black's d-pawn often goes to d6, and Black aims for a solid position with potential ...e5 break later on. }
4. e3 Be7
{ This move is much rarer than  4...Bb7  , but it has some subtleties.  Black wants to save a tempo for ...Ba6, so he develops his kingside bishop first. Also, Black now has a small positional threat of eliminating the London bishop with 5...Nh5. }
5. h3
{ As a general rule, when Black threatens Nh5, White needs to play this move to preserve the important London bishop. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3 { 6...Bb7  transposes to the4...Bb7 line. } 6... Ba6
{ This is the only thing Black can do to justify his last two moves. While White cannot avoid the exchange of these bishops, we retain some chances for an advantage with simple developing moves. }
7. O-O Bxd3
{ Exchanging the bishops immediately would help the white queen to develop to a good square }
8. Qxd3 c5 9. c4
{ White needs to gain more space and start attacking in the center and queenside. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Taking on d4 with the knight is better, as we do not want to have an isolated pawn or hanging pawns after  10.exd4?!  d5  . }
10... d6 { Black is solid but a bit passive. } 11. Bg3 Qd7 12. Nc3 Nc6 13. e4
{ This position resembles the Maroczy pawn structure in the Sicilian. White has some space advantage and easier play in the center. We will play Rfd1, Rac1, b3, then attack the d6-pawn. }
