[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6
{ This is the preferred move order for players who like to play Queen's Indian for Black. Peter Leko is one of the top GMs who employs this system consistently. With this setup, Black wants to develop his queenside bishop to b7 or sometimes trade the light-squared bishops with Ba6. He usually follows up with ...c5 and ...cxd4. Black's d-pawn often goes to d6, and Black aims for a solid position with potential ...e5 break later on. }
4. e3 Bb7
{ This move is a logical follow-up of the previous move. However, I also analyzed a few other options for Black. }
5. Bd3
{ I am recommending this move for White. We delay the move Nbd2 because this knight may be better placed on c3 in some cases, as you will see later. We should prioritize developing our kingside and aiming for e3-e4. }
5... Nh5
{ This move is better than 4...Nh5 because the black bishop is well placed on the long diagonal now. However, after exchanging the dark-squared bishops, Black does not have much counterplay. }
6. Bg5 Be7 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. c4
{ White needs to fight for a space advantage in the center. } 8... Qb4+
{ This move is risky for Black. White can sacrifice a pawn and get plenty of compensation. }
9. Nc3 Qxb2 10. Nb5 Bxf3
{ This move is forced, otherwise Black loses material. If  10...Qb4+  11.Nd2  , Black cannot defend the h5-knight and the c7-pawn at the same time.   If  10...Na6  11.Rb1  Qxa2  12.Ra1  Qb2  13.Rxa6  , White gets two minor pieces for the rook. }
11. gxf3 Qb4+ { White does not have Nd2 now, so we should move our king. } 12.
Kf1 Na6 13. Rb1 Qa5
{ This move looks awkward, but the black queen must stay there to guard the a6-knight.  13...Qe7  loses at least a pawn after  14.Qa4  c6  15.Qxa6  cxb5  16.Rxb5  g6  17.Rxb6  . }
14. Rb3
{ White threatens Ra3, so Black is forced to attack the white knight with his next move. }
14... c6 15. Ra3 Qb4 16. Rxa6 cxb5
{ After the exchange of the knights, Black survives the attack. However, the endgame is still quite unpleasant for him. }
17. Qb3 Qxb3 18. axb3
{ Black's queenside is very weak. White has multiple threats like Be4 or Ke2, Rha1. }
18... bxc4 19. bxc4 Nf6 20. Ke2
{ White will soon regain the a-pawn. We have better chances in this endgame mainly thanks to the fact that the white bishop is stronger than the black knight, and the b6-pawn is a clear target. }
