7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Similarly to 7...cxd4, if  8...cxd4  White should recapture with the c-pawn.  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  d5  11.Nc3  transposes to theline analyzed previously. }
8... d5
{ This move is not the most popular, but in my opinion the soundest continuation for Black. It may look a bit unnatural to close the long diagonal, but Black needs to prevent White from playing e4. The black knight can develop to c6 or d7, and Black can also try to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bd6 }
9. Nbd2 Bd6
{ This maneuver is similar to what we have seen in Part II. White should not worry about doubling our f-pawns as that will give us better control of the center. }
10. Qe2 { This move prevents ...Ba6 and prepares Rad1 or subsequent e4. } 10...
Qc7 { Black forces White to exchange the bishops with this move. } 11. Bxd6
Qxd6 12. Ne5
{ If Black had an extra move, he would love to play Nbd7 to prepare for ...e5, freeing up his position. Therefore, White needs to increase control in the center right away. }
12... Nc6 13. f4 Ne7 14. Rf2
{ White has good chances for a kingside attack. Our plan is Raf1, g4, Rg2, g5. }
