{ This standard move neutralizes the Nh5 threat by allowing our bishop a retreat to h2 when necessary. }
6... c5 7. c3
{ White is ready to recapture on d4 with the c-pawn, thus giving the c3-square for our knight. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Similarly to 7...cxd4, if  8...cxd4  White should recapture with the c-pawn.  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  d5  11.Nc3  transposes to theline analyzed previously. }
8... d5
{ This move is not the most popular, but in my opinion the soundest continuation for Black. It may look a bit unnatural to close the long diagonal, but Black needs to prevent White from playing e4. The black knight can develop to c6 or d7, and Black can also try to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bd6 }
9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. a4
{ This is a typical move to gain space on the queenside. 11. a5 is a positional threat. }
10... a6
{ This move prevents White's idea. If  11.a5?!  b5  , Black has a solid position with no weakness. }
11. Qb1
{ This move controls the e4-square and supports b4. White is ready to start the queenside battle. The natural-looking  11...h6  is strongly met by  12.b4  cxb4  13.cxb4  , and White has a clear plan on the queenside: Qb2, Rfc1, b5, Nf3-Ne5-Nc6, etc. }
11... c4
{ Black attempts to expand on the queenside with this move. Now White has to retreat the bishop and allow Black's next move. }
12. Bc2 b5 13. b4
{ Black is faced with a tough decision here: closing the queenside would lead to a passive position, but opening the queenside would leave him with a weakness on b5. }
13... cxb3
{ This move simplifies the position but Black may have a hard time defending his b5-pawn. }
14. Qxb3 Bc6
{ The black bishop must go here to defend the b5-pawn and creates the threat of ...bxa4. }
15. axb5 axb5
{ This move keeps a good control over the c4-square. However, the pawn is vulnerable on b5 and the black bishop is relatively passive on c6. }
16. Bd3 { White should target this pawn immediately. } 16... Qb6 17. Rfb1
{ We have reached a playable middlegame. The position is objectively equal, but the b5-pawn is a clear target for White. It is harder for Black to attack the c3-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Part IV: Slav Setup"]
[Black "A comment on 3.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5
{ In this chapter, we will study the setup when Black commits to an early d5 without moving the pawn in front of his king.   This position is also often be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . Black's idea is to develop his queenside bishop before playing e6, so he will not have any problem with that passive bishop as in the previous chapter. }
3. Bf4
{ This is the traditional approach to the London System. It has been analyzed very heavily by strong GMs in other Chessable courses. }
3... c5
{ This is considered Black's most ambitious response against the London System. I myself played many games with both colors in this line. }
4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ 5.c3  is slightly inaccurate here due to  5...Qb6  6.Qc2  Nh5  Black eliminates the London bishop and equalizes comfortably. }
5... Qb6
{ Black attacks the white pawns on b2 and d4 simultaneously. White can only keep one of them. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8. Bb5
{ I recently scored two nice wins against GM So in rapid and GM Shankland in blitz from this position. However, I believe it is not for everyone. Oftentimes, both sides have to memorize long lines with many sharp and unnatural moves. With chess engines getting stronger every day, the theory of this line will most likely change in the near future. As my goal is to build a lifetime repertoire for you, I feel that it is better to aim for slightly less known positions where our chances are in no way inferior compared to 3.Bf4.  For White players who are interested in the 3.Bf4 line, I suggest they investigate further Black's two main moves here:  8...g6  and  8...e6  . Both lead to complicated and playable positions for both sides. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Part IV: Slav Setup"]
[Black "3...c6 4.Qc2 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5
{ In this chapter, we will study the setup when Black commits to an early d5 without moving the pawn in front of his king.   This position is also often be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . Black's idea is to develop his queenside bishop before playing e6, so he will not have any problem with that passive bishop as in the previous chapter. }
3. c3
{ I have chosen to recommend this relatively rare move for White. It may look slow and harmless, but actually, it is quite interesting and has many finesses. First of all, White makes a generally useful move in the London System and waits to see which setup Black chooses before developing our London bishop. Secondly, this move is designed specifically to meet 3...c5, which is the standard response to 3.Bf4. Last but not least, the move 3.c3 gives White options to play Qb3 and attack the b7-pawn when the black light-squared bishop develops to f5.   In many cases, the arising positions will look nothing like a typical London System, but perhaps more similar to a Slav or Queen's Gambit Declined. White may not have an objective advantage, but we will accomplish the goal of our course: to get a playable position where we are better prepared than our opponent! }
3... c6
{ If Black copies White's setup with this move, White should try to disallow Bf5 by playing Qc2. }
4. Qc2 Bg4
{ This is a very natural and logical way to develop the bishop. Here White should aim for the bishop pair and potential to get a long-term advantage. }
5. Ne5 Bh5 6. Qf5
{ This unusual novelty creates the threat of Qh3 followed by g4. Black may face serious trouble if he is not careful.  6...Bg6  7.Qh3  White threatens Nxg6 and compromises Black's pawn structure.  7...Bxb1  8.Rxb1  White's position is a little bit more pleasant as we have the bishop pair and chances for a kingside attack. }
6... Nbd7 7. Qh3 { Now g4 is a very strong threat. } 7... Rg8
{ This move allows Black to recapture on g6 with his h-pawn, but the rook is oddly placed here. }
8. g4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. g5
{ After the exchange, White has the bishop pair. However, we must speed up our development in the next two moves, or we would not have any advantage. }
10... Nh5
{ The black knight must go here.  10...Ne4??  11.Qh7  wins the game right away for White. }
11. e4 { This is a pawn sacrifice for initiative. } 11... dxe4 12. Be3
{ White has the bishop pair and space advantage. We will regain the pawn soon with Nd2 and continue the attack with O-O-O, Bg2, Rhe1. }
