1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5
{ In this chapter, we will study the setup when Black commits to an early d5 without moving the pawn in front of his king.   This position is also often be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . Black's idea is to develop his queenside bishop before playing e6, so he will not have any problem with that passive bishop as in the previous chapter. }
3. c3
{ I have chosen to recommend this relatively rare move for White. It may look slow and harmless, but actually, it is quite interesting and has many finesses. First of all, White makes a generally useful move in the London System and waits to see which setup Black chooses before developing our London bishop. Secondly, this move is designed specifically to meet 3...c5, which is the standard response to 3.Bf4. Last but not least, the move 3.c3 gives White options to play Qb3 and attack the b7-pawn when the black light-squared bishop develops to f5.   In many cases, the arising positions will look nothing like a typical London System, but perhaps more similar to a Slav or Queen's Gambit Declined. White may not have an objective advantage, but we will accomplish the goal of our course: to get a playable position where we are better prepared than our opponent! }
3... c6
{ If Black copies White's setup with this move, White should try to disallow Bf5 by playing Qc2. }
4. Qc2 Bg4
{ This is a very natural and logical way to develop the bishop. Here White should aim for the bishop pair and potential to get a long-term advantage. }
5. Ne5 Bh5 6. Qf5
{ This unusual novelty creates the threat of Qh3 followed by g4. Black may face serious trouble if he is not careful.  6...Bg6  7.Qh3  White threatens Nxg6 and compromises Black's pawn structure.  7...Bxb1  8.Rxb1  White's position is a little bit more pleasant as we have the bishop pair and chances for a kingside attack. }
6... Nbd7 7. Qh3 { Now g4 is a very strong threat. } 7... Qc8
{ Black tries to exchange queen with this move. White should now make another move with our queen! }
8. Qh4 { This move renews the threat of g4. } 8... h6
{ This move looks logical, but it takes away the h6-square in a key variation. }
9. g4 g5
{ 9...Nxe5  is a mistake due to  10.dxe5  Qxg4  11.Qxg4  Nxg4  12.f4  and suddenly the black knight is trapped! }
10. Qg3 { All the tactics work in White's favor here. } 10... Nxe5
{ This for instance is a large mistake. } 11. dxe5 Ne4 12. Qg1
{ Black can't take on g4 due to the threatened fork with f3, and what's worse, the queen will now cover the c5-square. }
12... Bg6 13. f3 { The black knight is lost! } *

