[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5
{ In this chapter, we will study the setup when Black commits to an early d5 without moving the pawn in front of his king.   This position is also often be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . Black's idea is to develop his queenside bishop before playing e6, so he will not have any problem with that passive bishop as in the previous chapter. }
3. c3
{ I have chosen to recommend this relatively rare move for White. It may look slow and harmless, but actually, it is quite interesting and has many finesses. First of all, White makes a generally useful move in the London System and waits to see which setup Black chooses before developing our London bishop. Secondly, this move is designed specifically to meet 3...c5, which is the standard response to 3.Bf4. Last but not least, the move 3.c3 gives White options to play Qb3 and attack the b7-pawn when the black light-squared bishop develops to f5.   In many cases, the arising positions will look nothing like a typical London System, but perhaps more similar to a Slav or Queen's Gambit Declined. White may not have an objective advantage, but we will accomplish the goal of our course: to get a playable position where we are better prepared than our opponent! }
3... c6
{ If Black copies White's setup with this move, White should try to disallow Bf5 by playing Qc2. }
4. Qc2 Qc7
{ Black can try copying White's move again. In this case, White should continue with }
5. c4
{ This is already a novelty. White presents Black with a dilemma: either to take on c4 and give White the center, or play ...e6 and have a passive bishop on c8. Black cannot allow White to take on d5 as he will not be able to recapture with the c-pawn due to the pin on the c-file. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4
{ This position is very similar to a variation in the Slav Defence, with the only difference being that the black queen is on c7 instead of d8. His queen does not do much on c7, and in some instances may even hinder Black's play. We already have a very fresh and playable position here. It is impossible to analyze all possibilities here, but I recommend the Fianchetto setup for White. The game may continue with }
6... Bf5 7. g3 e6 8. Bg2
{ This bishop is very useful on the long diagonal. In case Black opens up with ...c5, the pawn on b7 will be a target for White to attack. }
8... Nbd7 9. O-O Be7 10. Nc3 O-O
{ We can again compare this position with the Slav variation where the black queen is on d8 instead of c7. In that Slav variation, Black always has threats like ...Nb6 or ...b5. But here with the queen on c7, White can safely get the bishop pair with }
11. Nh4
{ Black does not have Nb6 followed by Qxd4, so White is slightly better with space advantage. We can aim for e4, Qb3, Bf4 next. }
