7. Bg2 b6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 { White should play for e4. } 9... Bb7 10. e4 dxe4
{ 10...Nxe4  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Ng5  Nd7  13.Nxe4  leads to the same position. }
11. Ng5 { White wants to place a knight on e4. } 11... Nbd7 12. Ngxe4 Nxe4 13.
Nxe4 c5
{ If Black does not play this move, White will take the bishop on d6 followed by Rd1/Bf4 with a clear advantage thanks to the bishop pair. }
14. d5 exd5 15. cxd5
{ White has a little more space and more active pieces in the center. The d5-pawn may also pose some problems for Black down the road. White plans to continue with Rd1, Be3, a4. }
