[White "Part IV: Slav Setup"]
[Black "3...c5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5
{ In this chapter, we will study the setup when Black commits to an early d5 without moving the pawn in front of his king.   This position is also often be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  . Black's idea is to develop his queenside bishop before playing e6, so he will not have any problem with that passive bishop as in the previous chapter. }
3. c3
{ I have chosen to recommend this relatively rare move for White. It may look slow and harmless, but actually, it is quite interesting and has many finesses. First of all, White makes a generally useful move in the London System and waits to see which setup Black chooses before developing our London bishop. Secondly, this move is designed specifically to meet 3...c5, which is the standard response to 3.Bf4. Last but not least, the move 3.c3 gives White options to play Qb3 and attack the b7-pawn when the black light-squared bishop develops to f5.   In many cases, the arising positions will look nothing like a typical London System, but perhaps more similar to a Slav or Queen's Gambit Declined. White may not have an objective advantage, but we will accomplish the goal of our course: to get a playable position where we are better prepared than our opponent! }
3... c5
{ This is the critical response of the whole setup. Black challenges White's opening idea by playing ambitiously and energetically. }
4. dxc5
{ White must accept this pawn sacrifice if we hope to fight for any opening advantage. }
4... e6 { Black tries to regain the pawn as soon as possible. } 5. b4
{ We should hang on to this pawn for a few moves while developing our queenside. }
5... a5 6. e3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ After this move, Black will be able to regain the pawn. This variation has been tested many times recently at the top level, especially by Firouzja with White. }
8. Bb5+
{ White should exchange the light-squared bishops as that helps us complete our development. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+
{ 9...Qxd7?!  10.a4  bxc5  11.b5  This is similar to the main line, but Black is down two tempi. White can play like in the main line below with a clear advantage. }
9... Nbxd7 10. a4
{ We cannot keep our c5-pawn, so we should prepare to advance the b-pawn to b5 after Black takes on c5 with his pawn. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ The arising position is complex and unconventional: White has two connected passed pawns on the queenside, while Black has a protected passed pawn in the center. I believe the position is slightly easier to play for White, as we have a clear plan: to advance our queenside pawns. }
11... Ra7
{ This move was tried only once by GM So against GM Bluebaum. Black wants to put his queen on a8 and hold off the white pawns. }
12. O-O Qa8 13. Bd2 Bd6 { Here I have found a natural novelty for White. } 14.
a5
{ White should take the opportunity to advance our pawns as far as possible. }
14... O-O 15. Na3 { White creates a tactical threat with b6 followed by Nb5. }
15... Rb8 { This move runs into White's idea. } 16. b6 Nxb6 17. Nb5 Nc4 18.
Nxa7 Qxa7 19. Qa4
{ Black has some compensation for the exchange, but clearly White is in the driver's seat. We will continue with Rfb1 next and try to promote our passed pawn. This a-pawn is a major asset for White. }
