a5
{ White should take the opportunity to advance our pawns as far as possible. }
14... O-O 15. Na3 { White creates a tactical threat with b6 followed by Nb5. }
15... Ne4
{ Black threatens to exchange the white bishop and then take our pawn on a5. }
16. a6
{ The a-pawn is very safe now, and it limits the activity of the black rook and queen. Although Black has a blockage on b6, he cannot really capture the white pawn on b5. }
16... Rb8 17. Ba5 Bc7 18. Bxc7 Rxc7 19. Qc2
{ Without the bishops, Black does not have any counterplay on the queenside. White's next moves will be Rfb1 followed by Nd2. Black must be very careful not to allow the white pawns to advance. }
