{ 2...Nf6  3.c3  transposes toPart IV: Slav Setup. In this chapter, we will study Black's moves other than 2...Nf6. As a general rule, if Black makes unambitious moves, at some point White should play actively with  c4  and gain space on the queenside. }
2... e6 3. Bf4 Bd6 4. e3 Bxf4 5. exf4 Ne7
{ This knight is slightly less active on e7 than on f6. White can start a kingside attack immediately as the black knight does not control g4. }
6. h4 b6 7. h5 h6
{ Black must play this move to stop the white pawn from going to h6 and weaken Black's kingside. However, White now has a target to attack: the pawn on h6. }
8. g4
{ White wants to open up the kingside. Castling on this side is now very dangerous for Black. }
8... c5 9. Nc3
{ Black's king will not feel safe anywhere. White will castle long and prepare for the f5 or g5 break. }
