1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ 2...Nf6  3.c3  transposes toPart IV: Slav Setup. In this chapter, we will study Black's moves other than 2...Nf6. As a general rule, if Black makes unambitious moves, at some point White should play actively with  c4  and gain space on the queenside. }
2... Bf5
{ This bishop development is premature, as White's next move immediately highlights Black's queenside weakness. }
3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qb3
{ This move puts black queenside under pressure. Black does not have a good way to defend the pawn on b7. }
5... Nc6
{ White cannot take the pawn on b7 due to Nb4. However, the knight on c6 is slightly misplaced. }
6. Bg5
{ White continues with the development and is ready to meet Nb4 with Rc1, defending the c2-square. The black knight on f6 is also pinned, and White renews the threat of taking the pawn on d5. }
6... Bb4
{ Black pins the white knight with this move, thus he indirectly defends the d5-pawn. }
7. e3 a5
{ Black attempts to complicate the position with the threat of ...a4. Now I like a simple novelty. }
8. Qa4
{ This move stops ...a4. In the long run, White will have a better pawn structure. }
8... O-O 9. a3
{ White forces Black to release the tension.   9...Be7  10.Be2  leads to a slightly better position for White. The black knight on c6 is misplaced, and Black has several queenside weaknesses. }
9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Be2
{ After simplification of two pairs of minor pieces, White will complete the development with O-O, Rac1, Rfd1. At some point, White can exchange the pawns on d5 and then play c4. White has better control of the queenside and the center. }
