[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Part VI: Dutch Defence"]
[Black "2...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence is one of the most common responses to White's first move. The London System still works as a charm here, but we must be accurate with our move order. }
2. Nf3
{ It is preferable to develop this knight before the London bishop, so we have more flexibility in case Black does something unusual. }
2... g6
{ Once Black is committed to fianchettoing his kingside bishop, we should establish control of the center immediately. }
3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6
{ Black should not delay developing the kingside knight with this move. He should try  4...Nf6  5.Bf4  , which transposes to themain line. In this position, White can open up the center. }
5. e4
{ White challenges the black pawn on f5 and uses the opportunity to centralize the knight. The black king is slightly vulnerable. }
5... fxe4 6. Nxe4
{ This is the reason we want to prioritize developing our knights before the bishops. Now White has clear space advantage. }
6... Nf6 7. Bd3 { White keeps developing toward the center. } 7... Nc6
{ 7...Bg4  8.Neg5  Black has a major problem with his weakness on e6. White is prepared to play h3, chase the black bishop away, and start our attack on the kingside. }
8. h3
{ This move prevents Bg4 and makes sure that the white knight on f3 is unchallenged. }
8... O-O 9. O-O e5
{ Black must try to create some counterplay, otherwise he is just too passive. White's pieces are active, so we can afford to open up the center. }
10. dxe5
{ White should accept this pawn exchange to create some weaknesses in Black's position. }
10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4
{ With every exchange, White brings more pieces to the center. } 11... Nxe5 12.
Nxe5
{ 12...dxe5  may be a better move, but it leaves Black with an isolated pawn and the closed a1-h8 diagonal. White can continue with  13.Qb3  c6  14.Be3  when we have excellent bishops in the center. }
12... Bxe5 13. Bh6
{ White continues playing energetically and presents Black with another problem to solve. If Black does not want to exchange the dark-squared bishops, he would have to give up an exchange after  13...Re8  14.Bd5  Kh8  15.Bf7  . }
13... Bg7 14. Bxg7
{ It is advantageous for White to exchange these bishops, as now White's light-squared bishop is clearly more active than its counterpart. }
14... Kxg7 15. Qd2
{ White is going to start a kingside attack with Rae1, f4, g4. Black is significantly worse here due to his passivity and weakened kingside. }
