[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Part VI: Dutch Defence"]
[Black "2...Nf6 3.Bf4 e6 4.e3 b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence is one of the most common responses to White's first move. The London System still works as a charm here, but we must be accurate with our move order. }
2. Nf3
{ It is preferable to develop this knight before the London bishop, so we have more flexibility in case Black does something unusual. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ It is best to develop the London bishop first. White should only play c4, Nc3 after Black plays g6 or after White castles. }
3... e6
{ With this move, Black announces his intention not to fianchetto the kingside bishop. }
4. e3
{ White should not rush with c4 as that would allow Black the possibility to develop his bishop to b4 without being kicked away. }
4... b6
{ This setup resembles the Queen's Indian Defense. However, the pawn on f5 slightly weakens Black's position. }
5. Be2 { White should continue developing normally. } 5... Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4
{ After castling, White can bring the queenside knight to c3 and prepare for a central pawn break with d5. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3 Ne4
{ This is a typical move in similar lines in the Queen's Indian Defense. White can exchange the active knight and start a queenside attack. }
9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Bg3
{ This is a prophylactic move against potential g5 threats. It is not so easy for Black to complete his development. For instance,  10...d6  runs into  11.d5  Bxf3  12.Bxf3  e5  13.Bxe5!  dxe5  14.d6  c6  15.dxe7  Qxe7  16.Bxc6  with a small advantage for White. }
10... Bf6 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. b4
{ White will soon exchange the light-squared bishops with Bf3 and follow up with Rc1 and c5. Black has a passive position with little counterplay. }
*

