[White "Part VI: Dutch Defence"]
[Black "2...Nf6 3.Bf4 g6 4.c4 Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O 6.e3 d6 7.h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch Defence is one of the most common responses to White's first move. The London System still works as a charm here, but we must be accurate with our move order. }
2. Nf3
{ It is preferable to develop this knight before the London bishop, so we have more flexibility in case Black does something unusual. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ It is best to develop the London bishop first. White should only play c4, Nc3 after Black plays g6 or after White castles. }
3... g6
{ This is the preferred move order for black players who aim for the Leningrad System. }
4. c4
{ As noted above, once Black is committed to fianchettoing his bishop, White should play this move and develop the knight to c3. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e3 d6
{ The usual plan for Black in this setup is to play ...e5 and fight for the center. The London bishop is especially useful in battling against this idea. There are some subtleties for White here, such as when to play h3 or d5. }
7. h3
{ Normally, White would like to play this, however, it allows Black a concrete response. }
7... c5
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White is slightly behind in development. Black creates counterplay in the center and queenside. }
8. Bd3
{ White stops the black knight from coming to e4, however, the disadvantage of this move is that it reduces the support for the white pawn on d4.  8.d5  opens up the long diagonal for the black bishop.  8...Ne4  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Nd2  Bxb2  11.Rb1  Bc3  12.Be2  Qa5  . White cannot castle easily due to this pin on the knight. This is why we should play 7.Be2 instead of 7.h3. If Black tries the same idea there, we would be able to castle immediately after ...Bc3. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 Nh5 11. Bh2 e5
{ Black achieves this thematic break and the position remains very complicated. This is the reason I prefer 7.Be2 over 7.h3. }
