{ The black pawn on e4 is very weak, so he must enter concrete lines and hope to get a dynamic compensation. }
9... Bxd4 { This is the only way to justify Black's 7th move. } 10. exd4 Rxf4
11. g3 { White regains the pawn with some interest. } 11... Rf7 12. Nxe4 e5
{ Black must play this move to avoid future problems on the e-file. } 13. dxe5
Qe7 { Black takes advantage of the hanging knight on e4 to develop his queen }
14. Nf6+ { White transfers the knight to a better square with this check. }
14... Kg7 15. Nd5 Qxe5 16. Qd2 Bg4
{ Black creates counterplay and does not allow White to castle. } 17. f4 Qxe2+
18. Qxe2 Bxe2 19. Kxe2
{ White has better chances in this endgame as we have more space and an active knight. White can play on both sides of the board. The next moves can be Rae1, Kd2, b4, Kc3, h4, g4, etc. }
