{ The Dutch Defence is one of the most common responses to White's first move. The London System still works as a charm here, but we must be accurate with our move order. }
2. Nf3
{ It is preferable to develop this knight before the London bishop, so we have more flexibility in case Black does something unusual. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4
{ It is best to develop the London bishop first. White should only play c4, Nc3 after Black plays g6 or after White castles. }
3... g6
{ This is the preferred move order for black players who aim for the Leningrad System. }
4. c4
{ As noted above, once Black is committed to fianchettoing his bishop, White should play this move and develop the knight to c3. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e3 d6
{ The usual plan for Black in this setup is to play ...e5 and fight for the center. The London bishop is especially useful in battling against this idea. There are some subtleties for White here, such as when to play h3 or d5. }
7. Be2 { It is important to play this move before h3. } 7... Nc6
{ With this move, Black creates a tactical threat of ...Ne4. For instance, if  8.O-O  Ne4  , White cannot play  9.Nxe4?  fxe4  10.Nd2  Nxd4!  when Black is better.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1p1bp/2np1np1/5p2/2PP1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d5  e5  is also good for Black as he achieves his thematic move. }
8. Bg3
{ This move is necessary to prevent ...Ne4, and also prophylactic against ...e5. }
8... Qe8 { Black prepares for ... e5 with this move. } 9. O-O e5 10. c5
{ This is our normal response to ...e5: to start a queenside attack on c7 and d6 pawns. }
10... Ne4
{ Black complicates the position with this move, but White still keeps a small plus after }
11. cxd6 Nxg3
{ This move eliminates the London bishop but does not fully solve Black's problems. }
12. hxg3
{ 12...e4  13.Ng5  cxd6  14.Nh3  . With the knight coming to f4 and d5, and rook to c1, White has great pressure on the queenside. }
12... cxd6 13. Qb3+
{ White activates the queen and brings her to a3 to target Black's queenside pawns. }
13... Kh8 14. d5
{ After the black knight retreats, White continues with Nb5 and Rac1, highlighting the vulnerability of Black's queenside. White can also play Qa3 or double the rooks on the c-file. }
