{ This is the preferred move order for black players who aim for the Leningrad System. }
4. c4
{ As noted above, once Black is committed to fianchettoing his bishop, White should play this move and develop the knight to c3. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e3 d6
{ The usual plan for Black in this setup is to play ...e5 and fight for the center. The London bishop is especially useful in battling against this idea. There are some subtleties for White here, such as when to play h3 or d5. }
7. Be2 { It is important to play this move before h3. } 7... Nc6
{ With this move, Black creates a tactical threat of ...Ne4. For instance, if  8.O-O  Ne4  , White cannot play  9.Nxe4?  fxe4  10.Nd2  Nxd4!  when Black is better.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1p1bp/2np1np1/5p2/2PP1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d5  e5  is also good for Black as he achieves his thematic move. }
8. Bg3
{ This move is necessary to prevent ...Ne4, and also prophylactic against ...e5. }
8... h6 { This move prepares ...Nh5 } 9. h3
{ Now our London bishop can drop back to h2 in case of Nh5 } 9... e6
{ This approach to place the queen on e7 is too slow. White always has Nd5 to harass the black queen after ...e5. }
10. O-O Qe7 11. Rc1 b6 12. c5
{ This typical move opens the queenside and leaves Black with a weakness on d6 or c7. White has two threats now: d5 or cxd6 followed by Nb5. Black's response is almost forced. }
12... dxc5
{ 12...Bb7  is bad due to  13.cxd6  cxd6  14.d5  , when Black has too many weaknesses to defend. }
13. dxc5 Bb7
{ If given time, Black wants to play e5, Rfd8, Kh7 to defend everything and neutralize White's attack. }
14. Qb3
{ This move pins the e6- and b6-pawns and vacates the d1-square for the white rook. }
14... Kh7 15. Rfd1
{ All white pieces are on their ideal squares. Now White is ready for ideas such as cxb6 followed by Nb5 or Ne5. }
15... Rfd8
{ 15...e5  is met by  16.Qa3  with the threat of cxb6, exchanging the queens and winning the black pawn on e5. }
16. Qa3
{ It is difficult for Black to defend all his weaknesses. The game may continue with  16...a6  17.cxb6  Qxa3  18.bxa3  cxb6  19.Na4  Nd5  20.Bc4  Nce7  21.Bb3  , with some pressure on Black's queenside pawns. }
