1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 c6 5. e3
{ This move gives Black two equally sound extra options:  5...Nh5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2p2np1/3p4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  .   The more accurate move order would start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2p2np1/3p4/3P1B2/2N2N2/PPP1PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  . After this move, Black has nothing better than  5...Bg7  , then White will  go  6.e3  , achieving our desired position. }
5... Bg7 6. h3 { Now we transpose back toPart I. } 6... O-O 7. Be2 Qb6
{ I did not analyze this move in Part I. The reason is that the move accomplishes very little for Black, other than a simple threat, which White can neutralize easily. }
8. Rb1
{ Now the black queen is misplaced. White's plan is to open up the queenside with b2-b4-b5. The white rook will be perfectly placed on b1 in that case. }
8... Nbd7 9. O-O Re8 10. Bh2
{ 10.b4  This is a more direct way to play. Black is nowhere close to playing ...e5, while White has real threats with b5. Black's best move now is retreating his queen, wasting two tempi.  10...Qd8  11.b5⩲  White has a dangerous queenside attack. }
10... Nf8 11. b4
{ Finally, White found this plan. Black did not make any improvement with his pieces. }
11... Bf5 12. Nd2
{ 12.Na4!  White can already harass the black queen and transfer his knight to a better square.  12...Qd8  13.Nc5  b6  14.Na6  Rc8  15.Rc1  Ne4  16.c4±  All the white pieces are very well placed for the eventual opening of the queenside. Black has many weaknesses, especially his c6-pawn. }
12... N6d7 13. Na4 Qd8 14. Nc5
{ This move allows Black to simplify the position. White's advantage is gone.   14.g4!?  This is the only way to play for advantage. The bishop must retreat to e6, so Black does not have ...e5. White can then continue with his queenside play.  14...Be6  15.b5⩲ }
14... Nxc5 15. bxc5 b6 16. Ba6 Bc8 17. Bxc8 Rxc8 18. cxb6 axb6 19. c4 c5 20.
