1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. h3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3
Nc6 9. Nbd2 d5 10. Qe2 Bd6
{ This position is analyzed inPart III. My recommendation is  11.Rad1  , however, this game transposes eventually to the same position. }
11. Rfe1 Ne7
{ 11...Bxf4  White should not be worried about the double f-pawns as he has better control of the center.  12.exf4  cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4⩲ }
12. Rad1 Ng6 13. Bxg6
{ This is a very interesting concept. As the position is relatively closed, the white knights are better than the black bishop on b7. }
13... hxg6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne5
{ If Black's h-pawn is still on h7, Black would be fine with Nd7, f6. But here White has a strong attack on the h-file, and it is not easy to kick the knight away from e5. }
15... g5
{ 15...Nd7  16.f4±  White will soon start a kingside attack with Qg4, Ndf3, Ng5, Qh4.  Exchanging the knights with  16...Nxe5  17.fxe5  only helps White open up the f-file for his major pieces. }
16. f4 gxf4 17. Rf1
{ After this move, White's attack is very smooth. Black does not have enough pieces to defend his kingside. }
17... Nd7
{ 17...fxe3?  This move is not playable because of a strong tactical response.  18.Rxf6  exd2  19.Rxd2  gxf6  20.Qg4+  Kh7  21.Rd3+-  Black is getting checkmated. }
18. Qh5 Nf6 { 18...fxe3  19.Nxf7  19...Rxf7  20.Qxf7+  Kh7  21.Rf4+- } 19. Qh4
