29. b3 Qe8 30. h4 h5 31. Rd6 b5 32. Qd5+ Kh7 33. Rb6 Rb8 34. Re6 Qf8 35. Qd1
Qf7 36. Ra6 a4 37. bxa4 bxa4 38. Rxa4 Rb2 39. a3 Kg6 40. Rb4 Ra2 41. a4 Qc7 42.
Qf3 Qd7 43. Rc4 Kh6 44. Qf5 Qxf5 45. exf5 Ra3 46. Rc8 Kh7 47. Ra8 e4 48. a5 e3
49. fxe3 Rxe3 50. a6 Re5 51. a7 Ra5 52. g4 hxg4
{ This is the losing mistake.   52...Ra2+□  Black must keep giving checks and force the white king to go far away from the kingside before capturing the g4-pawn.  53.Kg3  Ra3+  54.Kf2  Ra2+  55.Ke3  Ra3+= }
53. Kg3
{ Black cannot defend the g4-pawn now. White will regain this pawn, then move the king to f7 and play h4-h5-h6 to undermine Black's kingside pawns. This is a theoretical win for White. }
53... Ra3+ 54. Kxg4 Ra4+ 55. Kf3 Ra1 56. Ke4 Ra5 57. Kd4 Ra1 58. Kd5 Ra6 59. h5
